<HEADLINE>
<P>
OUTTAKES: OVERLOOKED? 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By John M. Wilson 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Despite a slew of celebs, who helped net a hefty $85,000 for the evening, the 
AIDS Hospice Foundation's Oscar night fund-raiser at the Directors Guild of 
America got scant press coverage last week. One trade paper columnist 
mistakenly referred to it as "the DGA party." 
</P>
<P>
A spokesman for the evening attributed the lack of media attention to a soft 
publicity push: "Since it was our first one, we didn't want to oversell." 
</P>
<P>
The Schutrum-Piteo Foundation, a nonprofit group that provides care to single 
seniors, underwrote the event, which was produced by the Friends of the AIDS 
Hospice. Maple Drive, 72 Market St. and a dozen other posh restaurants provided 
food and waiters. Studios pitched in personnel. And so on. 
</P>
<P>
In a unique fund-raising twist, the foundation arranged for sponsors to put up 
$1,000 for every celebrity who signed a guest book before the crowd. Among the 
stars showing up: Angelica Huston, ex-Gov. Jerry Brown, Edward James Olmos, 
Melanie Griffith and Don Johnson, Dudley Moore, Sally Kirkland, Robert Downey 
Jr., Estelle Getty, Rob Lowe. Bob Goen, host of the daytime "Wheel of Fortune," 
emceed. 
</P>
<P>
Biggest moment of the evening: when "Common Threads: Stories From the (AIDS) 
Quilt" won the Oscar for best documentary. John M. Wilson 
</P>
</TEXT>
