118 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
CURRENT PAPERBACKS: INTIMACY BY SUSAN CHACE (PLUME: $7.95) 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By CHARLES SOLOMON 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
A fragmented, inconclusive novel about an alcoholic woman who somehow survives 
the disease, despite a series of weird adventures that include a suicide 
attempt and a dalliance with her brother-in-law. 
</P>
<P>
The narration bounces about confusingly, shifting time and voice at the drop of 
a glass. The constant switching between Mary Cronstein's version of events and 
her friends' accounts may represent an attempt to re-create the fog of acute 
alcoholism, but Susan Chace probably makes extensive use of other characters 
because Cronstein's incessant whining bores her as heartily as it does the 
reader. Critics have ceased to announce the death of the novel, but "Intimacy" 
is at least badly wounded. 
</P>
</TEXT>
